      "name": "Foundation Forge",
      "tagline": "Build the Platform",
      "weeks": "Weeks 1–5",
      "focuses": [
        "Build movement quality, spine and knee resilience, and a controlled aerobic base.",
        "Re-groove bilateral strength patterns and establish baseline RPE awareness."
      ],
      "message": {
        "paragraphs": [
          "Ghazal, this first cycle is the platform everything else stands on. With 15 years of lifting behind you and a body that's carried lumbar and knee history, the job right now isn't to chase intensity — it's to re-teach your joints to move under load with complete control.",
          "Focus mentally on precision over effort: every rep owned, every landing quiet, every brace intentional. This is where we earn the right to go heavy in Cycle 2."
        ],
        "outcomes": [
          "Cleaner squat mechanics under tempo-controlled load",
          "A core that holds under rotation and anti-rotation demands",
          "Noticeable drop in body fat from Zone 2 + interval work",
          "Knees that feel stable and pain-free on plyometrics",
          "Baseline RPE awareness across all main lifts",
          "Restored shoulder balance for serve durability"
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "num": 2,
      "name": "Strength Engine",
      "weeks": "Weeks 6–10",
      "focuses": [
        "Drive maximal strength through moderate loads (RPE 7–8) with unilateral emphasis.",
        "Introduce tempo-controlled plyometrics to prep tendons for court load."
      ],
      "teaser": {
        "subtitle": "You've built the platform. Now we load it.",
        "paragraphs": [
          "Cycle 2 is where the foundation gets tested. Once your joints prove they can handle controlled load, we stop protecting and start building — heavier, more unilateral, more demanding on every system we've prepped here.",
          "The work gets quieter but the adaptation gets louder. Do Cycle 1 right, and you unlock a version of strength your tennis has never had access to."
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "num": 3,
      "name": "Power Translator",
      "weeks": "Weeks 11–15",
      "focuses": [
        "Convert strength to sport-specific power, rotational speed, and change-of-direction.",
        "Layer in reactive plyos and shoulder ballistics tied to tennis mechanics."
      ]
    },
    {
      "num": 4,
      "name": "Metabolic Shift",
      "weeks": "Weeks 16–20",
      "focuses": [
        "Aggressive body composition phase through elevated volume conditioning and repeat-effort work.",
        "Preserve strength with short, heavy exposures twice weekly."
      ]
    },
    {
      "num": 5,
      "name": "Court-Ready Peak",
      "weeks": "Weeks 21–25",
      "focuses": [
        "Peak speed, agility, and on-court durability for match-quality output.",
